{"code":1,"isDone":false,"toInsertArticleList":[{"createdTime":"2020-09-05 16:41:27","updatedTime":"2020-09-05 16:41:27","title":"Simplicity Is the Name of My Fall Fashion Game—These 6 Easy Trends Are the Best","link":"http://feeds.whowhatwear.com/~r/WhoWhatWear/~3/rU2TOtfC9vo/simple-fall-trend","description":"<p>If I had to sum up my style into a few words, “simple” would definitely make it on the list. Yep, the bulk of my closet is comprised of those low-key, <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/versatile-fashion\" target=\"_blank\">elevated basics</a> that can be mixed and matched to create, in my eyes, effortless outfits. Given that <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/easy-fashion-trends\" target=\"_blank\">simplicity is the name of my fashion game</a>, I typically gravitate towards those easier, versatile picks when I’m shopping or sourcing new trends. For fall specifically, there are six specific looks that have particularly caught my eye as I’ve been doing market research.</p><p>Intrigued? Below you’ll uncover the six easy trends that I think are worth noting for the season. As you’ll see, all of the looks coming your way are forward yet still simple in nature because they could be paired with a range of either basics or trendier items. advice given their expertise in mastering those easy-yet-chic silhouettes for that on-the-go lifestyle. Influencer and model <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/ext?tl=wVvpPraUghkQqWD63COiKm2nxAUQt2u_q9ka9cF7ETJyKOSFPejYQJ0XEViHjGCBxtgOqh4UoQ\" target=\"_blank\">Elaine Davis</a> is one of said experts. In fact, we recently highlighted the <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/dress-trends\" target=\"_blank\">dress trends</a> and <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/easy-fashion-over-50\" target=\"_blank\">wardrobe essentials she covets</a>. She also mentioned to us that, given the fact that she’s lived in NYC her entire life (38 years as an adult), she’s experimented with a range of shoe styles to keep comfortable while running around in the city. And yep, <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/summer-outfits-with-sneakers\" target=\"_blank\">fashionable sneakers</a> just happen to be one of her go-to choices.</p><p>\"Since I’m constantly on the go, I need to keep it comfy most days but yet pulled together,\" she told us. \"I’ve always loved a good sneaker and find that any outfit can still look über-chic worn with the right pair.\"</p><p>With that in mind, we thought there could be some interest in learning more about the specific sneaker outfits Davis wears to keep it simple and stylish in her day to day. To showcase said ‘fits, she shared with us six of her go-to looks at the moment, complete with styling ideas.</p><p>Below you’ll uncover A+ outfit ideas along with inspired shopping picks if something 16:41:27","updatedTime":"2020-09-05 16:41:27","title":"I've Been Bleaching My Hair for 15 Years—Here's How I Still Have Hair on My Head","link":"http://feeds.whowhatwear.com/~r/WhoWhatWear/~3/GEJjhfr9ohw/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage","description":"<p>Hello, my name is Erin Jahns, and I bleach the hell out of my hair. It's been going on for 15 years (I'm 26, and my first-ever color job was in fifth grade), and despite the amount of turmoil my strands have endured, I plan on being as <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/best-hair-color-for-my-skin-tone\" target=\"_blank\">blonde</a> as physically possible until my dying day. Or, at least, until my hair goes white—we'll see what happens first.</p><p>But first, some context. As a baby and through most of grade school, I was as blonde as blonde could be. Of course, at the time, I couldn't have cared less about the color of my hair, and if anything, I probably wanted blue, glitter-streaked highlights like the Spice Girls or edgy black lowlights à la Christina. The only reason I begged for highlights when I reached the fifth grade was that I thought I'd look \"glamorous\" (lol), and it's what all the cool girls were doing. So naturally, I begged my mom and dad for an appointment until my mom finally acquiesced and brought me along to her next salon appointment.</p><p>Peroxide zebra stripes were my first foray into the world of fake blonde hair, and from that day onward, I never went back. As I got older, my natural baby blonde turned into dirty dishwater, thus my foiling sessions became increasingly regular and increasingly hard on my hair. By the end of high school, I was asking colorists for full bleach and tones (so I was 100% bleached versus just heavily highlighted), and by the time I got to college, it's fair to say my hair was in a legitimately sorry state. Not horrible, but on the brink of disaster if I wasn't ultra careful with how I cared for and treated it. Am I doing a good job of foreshadowing my impending hair doom?</p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/282893/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage-282893-1570224351528-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p>Most people, at some point in their life, will have some kind of hair disaster. And while I had hoped I'd gotten mine out of the way in 1997 when my sister took me for a bowl cut at Kid's Hair, I wasn't so lucky. During my sophomore year of college, I experienced what my family, friends, and I refer to as \"The Bleach Apocolypse of 2013.\" After receiving a full head of highlights at a highly regarded salon in Minneapolis (where I'm from), I was left completely unhappy with the color. The end result was an ashy, mouse-like shade of brown with weird tones of blue and purple (probably from some kind of toning mishap), and I was beyond confused how the colorist had managed to stray so far from the bright, buttery-white blonde I'd always been.</p><p>In a panic, and because I had spent over $300 for said color, I begged her for options as to how she could fix it immediately. In hindsight, I should have sucked it up and sought out a different professional at another salon weeks later, but I had worked myself into a <em>state </em>and was completely desperate for an immediate solution. Also panicked (and a tad annoyed), the colorist told me the only way she could transform me into the bright blonde I wanted was to re-bleach <em>over</em> all of the highlights she had just foiled. (If you're cringing, you should be—that's legitimately the worst thing you can do to freshly weakened, colored hair, and her right to color hair should be revoked.) But, as I said, I was panicked and immediately accepted her offer even though she should have known better, apologized, and sent me home. </p><p>Fast-forward about one and a half hours later, and I was sitting in my car, bawling my eyes out with a wet, tangled, bleached-off disaster on top of my head. The bleaching was an entirely horrible idea and as the colorist washed my hair and attempted to comb through it, I watched in terror as fists of hair quite literally fell off my head. I know it might sound silly, and there are certainly larger world issues than a bleached hair disaster. At the time, I truly thought I was going to have to shave my head, and as much as I admire stars like Joey King, Charlize Theron, and Natalie Portman, I'm not an actress, and I don't have the cheekbones. </p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/282893/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage-282893-1570224366014-main.1200x1365uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p>Of course, the trials and tribulations I faced post-apocalypse are long and detailed enough for a novel, but long story short, I was, in the end, able to salvage my blonde hair. I poured hours and hours into research, babysitting check after babysitting check into rehabilitation products, and even more hours and babysitting checks at a different salon, getting trims, treatments, and consistent TLC. (The morning after the disaster I went to an Aveda salon where—I kid you not—I became a staff project and am still remembered to this day.)</p><p>It took about three years for my hair to bounce back, and up until a year or two ago—right around when I moved to L.A. to become a beauty editor—I was convinced my hair would never be the same. I still struggled to grow it out, and even though I had cut back on my highlight appointments (I think I went at least six months without getting so much as close to heat or peroxide post-trauma), colorists never seemed to get the tone right and my hair perpetually felt like straw.</p><p>Until, that is, I met my two fairy hair godparents, celebrity hairstylist <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/ext?tl=YXcjcroYeDLc_I_tR5JSVjKGk-Oi0_f-2nB5kAvOw39kMZxVqsxZLQLTeMbNKDPvSStTCc6CnC_PAOiyZg\" target=\"_blank\">Cervando Maldonado </a>and celebrity colorist <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/ext?tl=jO09gLwVf106CRUqmWAtTfAntqRCXEdjYPBL0FYwHwFzJju8yJWAiOlvFAT1H0NVP0kwe92FIprpAfMEU8w\" target=\"_blank\">Cassondra Kaeding</a>. I met Cervando week one of my job as assistant beauty editor for Byrdie, and (bless him to infinity) he's taken me under his wing and helped bring my hair to health and lengths I never thought possible as a blonde. He's the only one I've let touch my hair, style- and cut-wise, since arriving in L.A., and I credit his amazing snipping genius and practical hair tips (get yourself avocado or coconut oil and apply it to your ends as much as possible) for reviving my hair over the past two years.</p><p>That said, even though my cut and length were on the right track, I was still consistently frustrated with my color (even in as star-studded of a town as L.A.), and it wasn't until Maldonado introduced me to Kaeding at his West Hollywood salon, <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/ext?tl=K73CPcUGzKa6qisE2vrHQ2BPKe_og7Qc4dSI-MbI_nG9_cp3jkUrejFUxMTEj-kM29oYe1hTzuJX\" target=\"_blank\">454 North</a>, that I truly felt I had found my long-lost color soulmate. I've met countless celebrity colorists thanks to my day job, but Kaeding is one of <em>the</em> most sought-after colorists in the industry right now, and she's also a complete and utter perfectionist when it comes to her art, technique, and reputation as a colorist. In short, she's the only kind of person you want to entrust your fragile hair with.</p><p>Unlike that colorist back in 2013, Kaeding actually told me she wouldn't touch my hair with any kind of color during our initial appointment (she's all about integrity and refuses to administer any risky behavior that could weaken or damage susceptible strands) and despite my disappointment, I waited an additional three weeks on top of the 10 I'd already waited so she could wield her magic. And, wield she did. Not only did Kaeding give me the <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/blonde-hair-colors-for-every-skin-tone\" target=\"_blank\">best blonde hair</a> job of my entire 26 years, but she also kept literally every single hair on my head. My strands have never been so long or so blonde, and everyone I see and talk to (even other celebrity hairstylists and colorists) are truly in awe of how healthy my hair is despite how bleached it is. Kaeding is talented enough to create an enigma out of me, and I couldn't be more grateful. </p><p>To celebrate, and because I get so, SO many DMs and questions about how to fix bleached hair, I'm using my own experience as a forever blonde (I refer to myself as an unofficial official color expert) and Kaeding's <em>legitimate</em> expertise to provide a complete—and hopefully helpful—guide for blonde haircare below. Ahead, all of our combined best tips for how to care for and fix bleached, post-apocalyptic blonde hair. Keep scrolling!</p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/282893/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage-282893-1570224371400-main.1200x1365uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p>The very first order of business post-bleach-apocalypse back in 2013 was a haircut. The stylist I saw said that although they would give me a protein and moisture treatment to help stop the immediate breakage (my hair kept falling and falling), I would continue to shed, so the best thing I could do was to part with as much length as I could emotionally handle. Not only would the cut help even out the <em>look</em> of my hair, it would also help prevent further splits and snaps. At the time, he chopped my boob-length hair to my collarbones, and I was diligent about coming into the salon for trims every month or two.</p><p>Years later, my cadence is every three months or so, and I make sure to see the same stylist (Maldonado) who knows my hair's history and my goals for length and thickness. My hair has never been so long or as thick, and I attribute that in part to my consistency with trims—even if it's just a dusting off the ends prior to a coloring appointment (which Kaeding always recommends pre-bleach).</p><p>Please learn from my mistake here, and before you go in for color with a new professional, stop by the salon for a consultation. Not only will you get a feel for the colorist and see their other clients' hair, you'll also be able to make a game plan with them to ensure you get the exact color you want without sacrificing the health of your hair. As I mentioned above, the first time I was booked to see Kaeding, I was scheduled for an allover highlight, but when I went in to see her, she had me go home and grow out my hair for another three weeks and said I'd be better off getting a bleach and tone rather than highlights considering how blonde I wanted to be and how inconsistent I'd been with different colorists since being in L.A. </p><p>\"We decided to take the bleach and tone approach because during our consult you expressed that the color hadn't been quite right,\" she explains. \"There were some gold undertones you weren't fond of that needed to be eliminated, and your hair was in good enough condition. I knew that I would be able to go through, take my time, and get you to the desired bright blonde you have always wanted!\"</p><p>Again, please learn from my deadly error, and do a lot of research when searching for your perfect colorist and don't solely rely on a salon's name or owner. I've seen more colorists and been to more salons than I could count on my fingers and toes, and just because a salon is owned by a famous name or has a \"good reputation\" doesn't speak to every single stylist or colorist housed there. (Although I can vouch for everyone at 454 North—its team is heaven-sent.)</p><p>Even being in an industry city like L.A., I've had <em>some</em> pretty terrible experiences and some pretty terrible color. When I met Kaeding, it was like a breath of fresh air. She took her time, she was relaxed, and I felt safe in her hands. She also came recommended by Maldonado, whom I 110% trusted, and her Instagram showcases a lot of her work so I could rest assured she was well-versed in the color blonde I was hoping for. Bleaching is a really intense (and scientific) process, and going to the wrong person can be the do-or-die factor when it comes to both the color and integrity of your hair. </p><p>\"Bleaching is really tough,\" Kaeding agrees. \"It's easy to over-process the hair, which will cause extreme dryness or even breakage. My advice to other colorists is to take your time, do the work, and absolutely don’t rush. If both time and care are put into the application, your hair will stay healthier and longer, which means you can stay blonder longer.</p><p>\"What I did was coat the previously bleached, highlighted hair with Redken's <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/ext?tl=lqnPRfmJRpV3Bzq_lD1gM92rUI4qV-Ed-_FHq8Xls1YScUIDtC0ifY1B_P8vXiK0Z1Me5DWd2rwa\" target=\"_blank\">All Soft Heavy Cream Super Treatment Mask</a> ($22). This helps the new bleach I was going to be applying from overlapping onto the old, pre-lightened hair. I only applied bleach to the regrowth, and I put about a four-inch-long piece of cotton between each thin section, which acts as a barrier so the bleach doesn’t expand onto old blonde and also helps absorb any excess bleach.\"</p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/282893/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage-282893-1570224404961-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption>If you want to have super-blonde and super-healthy hair, lots of heat styling just isn't in your foreseeable future. (Sorry!) I didn't TOUCH a blow-dryer or my beloved flat iron for months and months after my bleaching disaster, and unless I absolutely have to, I still airdry my hair whenever possible and avoid my collection of hot tools, which, Kaeding completely supports, especially right after you've done major color or bleach. \"It depends on the client's severity of breakage, but the best thing to do after your color appointment is to leave your hair alone,\" she confirms. \"Try not to do any more chemical processes until your colorist gives you the green light or tells you to come back in. Excessive bleaching will only worsen your hair's health, and you need to give it time to recover. Also avoid heat styling; using hot tools on damaged hair will cause more breakage.\" When I do blow-dry my hair, I use a high-quality dryer like this above from T3, which was created with your strands' health and integrity in mind. But most of the time, I work with hair-healthy leave-ins that encourage and enhance my natural texture—no wands or irons necessary. (The below spray from IGK is my fave.)</figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/282893/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage-282893-1570224410720-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/282893/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage-282893-1570224418354-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption>Not to wax poetic on the importance of not washing your hair every day, but… please don't wash your hair every day. I personally aim for about twice a week, which has been a game-changer as far as keeping my color vibrant and fresh in addition to expediting hair growth. Kaeding loves Redken's Color Extend Magnetics Shampoo ($39) and Conditioner ($39), which are sulfate-free (this is important!) and lightweight but packed with hydrating and strengthening ingredients to help your hair recover post–bleaching trauma.  As far as purple shampoo, both Kaeding and I recommend using as-needed. I won't purple my hair until two or three weeks post-color and only every couple of weeks thereafter. In fact, I have better luck with salon-quality clarifying treatments (like the below from Malibu C), which completely nix brassiness and discoloration instead of just counteracting with a violet shampoo formula. Ask your colorist what they'd prescribe as far as purple shampoo, but you probably need it less than you (and the hair product market!) think. Right now, I'm loving Amika's formula, which was a recommendation from a fellow platinum blonde at WWW HQ. (Thanks, Dev!)</figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/282893/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage-282893-1570224421761-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/282893/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage-282893-1570224426293-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/282893/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage-282893-1570224431863-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption>Surprise, surprise, don't follow my 2013 lead by pre-gaming a bleaching process with more bleaching. Instead, in the weeks prior to the big color appointment, you should flood your system with the essential vitamins, nutrients, and hydration to encourage healthy, strong strands.  \"Before a big bleach process, I like to tell clients to do a hair mask once a week, and to take hair vitamins to make sure your hair is healthy and strong,\" Kaeding tells me. \"Keep hydrated—what you put in your body does impact the state of your skin, nails, AND hair. Drink lots of water, and eat fruits and vegetables that are high in water content.\" I swear by Hum's vegan hair gummies (they've truly made a difference with how fast and long my hair has grown), but Nutrafol is another favorite among both myself and other A-list hair professionals I've talked to. And yes, I'm that annoying girl that makes it a personal goal to drink at least 80 ounces of water per day. But, I do think Kaeding is right; it actually makes a difference. I also eat really clean and make sure I get ample protein from high-quality sources (legumes, salmon, etc.) plus healthy fats from nuts, seeds, avocados, and the like. </figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/282893/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage-282893-1570224444499-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/282893/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage-282893-1591740009848-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption>I'll admit watching that colorist attempt to comb through my bleached-off hair all those years ago still gives me nightmares, and to this day, I baby the eff out of my hair. In addition to using my favorite products religiously, I also take painstaking care when it comes to detangling and brushing my hair. I strictly use a wide-tooth comb on damp hair, starting with my ends, and working my way up, and use my favorite Shine Enhancer brush from Wet Brush only when completely necessary on my dry strands. It's even gotten to the point where I bring my comb with me to any kind of hair or blowout appointment and insist the stylist use it to detangle—unpopular opinion, but it results in significantly less breakage and fallout than a Wet Brush or Tangle Teezer. </figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/282893/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage-282893-1570224462889-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p>Hair masks are a major part of bleached hair recovery, and I try to do one every single week (bearing in mind I only wash my hair twice a week), so basically every other wash. I rotate between Olaplex's <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/ext?tl=l1rSzVTwJ9tVlZk-E7xeTx2RQrjPnalXOKVaiiEwPMcM4XgkWhy_Ca65s-yRywCyNydrH6HwkzqB\" target=\"_blank\">Hair Perfector No. 3</a> ($28) and any of the seven formulas below depending on what my hair needs. If it feels like it's dry, I'll pick one that's more moisturizing; if I feel like it's weak and prone to snapping more than usual, I'll grab one that has more protein and is geared toward strengthening.</p><p>Kaeding is also on board with my hardcore masking habit and recommends a once-per-week cadence to her clients. She loves Redken's <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/ext?tl=ldc5Ckd6vQ-lELmjchwUWU_RC28Osu3u14EUV7MAoWeG4jfi2cQ0F0TyXd-G34d9Lk3PjolSbfRF\" target=\"_blank\">Color Extend Blondage Mask</a> ($29), which also helps brighten and maintain lightened hair.</p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/282893/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage-282893-1570224483285-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption>I use Olaplex every other week to keep my strands strong and less prone to breakage. It needs to go on wet hair to be effective, and I'll often wrap my hair into a bun, go to work and the gym, then rinse it out before I shampoo and condition when I get home. </figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/282893/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage-282893-1570224500287-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption>I haven't been using this mask as much recently, but I absolutely swear it has miraculous superpowers. Post-apocalypse, I practically wore it 24/7 and used it as a daily conditioner, leave-in, and mask. The name doesn't lie, and even years later, I haven't found too many formulas that can compete with it. </figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/282893/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage-282893-1570224504123-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption>If you're looking for an affordable drugstore find that feels super luxurious and truly works wonders on damaged, bleached hair, I highly recommend this fan favorite from celebrity hairstylist Kristin Ess. It's deeply nourishing and helps build strength and stamina back into weakened strands. </figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/282893/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage-282893-1570224508777-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption>This is one of the most iconic hair masks in the business and for good reason. Developed by legendary hair genius Christophe Robin himself, it's enriched with amazing luxe ingredients like prickly pear seed oil and inula flower extract to flood parched strands with moisture and repair any lingering damage that's compromising your growth goals. </figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/282893/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage-282893-1591740835405-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption>I've turned so many fellow blondes onto this protein-rich mask from Davines. It's so dreamy, and, I swear, legitimately glues broken strands back together again. That said, it IS potent, so make sure you don't let it marinate longer than the recommended 10 to 30 minutes, and don't use it more than every few weeks or so. I usually apply it monthly in lieu of conditioner for 15 minutes. Does the trick! </figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/282893/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage-282893-1570224517080-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption>This was a recent Violet Grey find (along with my beloved Christophe Robin pick) that I've been really into lately and which has had a very positive impact on the softness and strength of my hair. It smells amazing (not a bad perk!) and utilizes the brand's signature Alpha Keratin 60ku complex to revive hair with shine, mega-hydration, and durability for more gloss and less snapping. </figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/282893/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage-282893-1591741014070-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption>How you choose to wrap and handle your hair when it's damp might seem innocent enough, but if you're pulling and yanking too aggressively or using the wrong materials, it can bear serious consequences. Instead of wrapping my hair with a heavy, frizz-promoting towel, I now only ever use these Microfiber Hair Turbans from Aquis. They're beloved within the beauty industry and promote faster drying time, more shine, longer-lasting color, and less breakage. Plus, they're lightweight and won't break your neck. </figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/282893/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage-282893-1570224524242-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption>Folks, silk pillowcases are a game-changer, and I notice a significant difference with the breakage around my hairline if I'm without one (i.e. when I'm traveling or sleeping at a friend's or S.O.'s.) I recommend getting a few of these for a multitude of reasons: They do wonders for keeping hair smooth, and they prolong your style so you don't have to wash as often. </figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/282893/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage-282893-1570224529386-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption>In the same vein, I swear by these big fluffy silk scrunchies. I pull my hair into a ponytail at the very tip-top of my head before tucking my ends through into a big floppy bun. I might look like Michelle Tanner, but I have less breakage and more shine than I did before starting the ritual. </figcaption></figure></p><p>Aside from shampoo, conditioner, masks, and my beloved air-dry spray (shown above from IGK), the only products I ever use in my hair are heat protecting and detangling leave-in conditioners, serums, and clear oils. After I unwrap my hair from the turban, I'll smooth a nickel-size amount of hair oil (always clear if you're blonde!) into the entire length of my hair, and then I'll spritz through with my leave-in. If I feel like my hair needs even more TLC, I might use another specialized serum or cream, but it's just as needed, and again, just depending on what my hair is feeling and looking like. My favorites are below!</p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/282893/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage-282893-1570224535692-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption>I've used this lightweight clear oil from Verb for YEARS. I'm obsessed, and it's one of the first products I always recommend to anyone who has hair but especially for blondes. </figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/282893/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage-282893-1570224540191-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption>This majestic marula oil–spiked elixir from Reverie is another all-time favorite. It's not greasy or heavy like so many oils out there and features exotic, nourishing, and color-protecting benefactors like crambe abyssinica seed oil for hydration and elasticity along with a dose of squalane for heat and color protection. </figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/282893/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage-282893-1570224590821-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption>I'm obsessed with these drops from Oribe even though I don't use them every time I wash or style my hair. The customizability factor is genius (just add a few drops to whatever styling product you fancy), and they're chock-full of the essential nutrients parched just-bleached hair is starved for. (Think vitamins, linoleic acid, biotin, and sea kelp extract.)</figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/282893/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage-282893-1570224607911-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption>This is my be-all and end-all leave-in conditioner. I've tried SO many, but I come back to this one again and again since my initial bleaching disaster. It smells amazing, boasts heat protection, detangling prowess, and a ton of other benefits. It's also so lightweight and moisturizing that it's almost impossible to OD—even if you get a little carried away with spritzing. It turns straw strands into velvet. </figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/282893/how-to-fix-bleached-hair-damage-282893-1570224613106-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption>Last but not least, don't forget your ends. I use this as needed in either damp or dry hair. Pea protein, hydrolized quinoa, and baobab seed oil work together to aid in heat protection, color enhancement, hydration, shine, and the sealing of decrepit split ends.  Up next: These 5 Colors Look Incredible on Blondes. 16:41:27","updatedTime":"2020-09-05 16:41:27","title":"A Celebrity Makeup Artist Told Me 4 Tips to Look Younger (If You're Into That)","link":"http://feeds.whowhatwear.com/~r/WhoWhatWear/~3/oDaDrcYPYRg/makeup-tips-to-look-younger","description":"<p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/284330/makeup-tips-to-look-younger-284330-1581616969461-main.1080x1080uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p>Celebrity makeup artists are like gatekeepers to the <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/best-beauty-products-to-try\" target=\"_blank\">best products</a>, <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/what-is-eyebrow-lamination\" target=\"_blank\">treatments</a>, and techniques for maintaining glowing skin. They have access to all the top brands and beauty experts and regularly touch the faces of some of the world's most famous women, so they know a thing or two when it comes to creating <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/best-concealers-for-mature-skin\" target=\"_blank\">a youthful appearance.</a> Some of the techniques they use are better left to the pros, but I wanted to know the easy tricks that we mere mortals could use in our day-to-day routines to amp up our makeup looks.</p><p>I reached out to celebrity makeup artist <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/ext?tl=SuiMuDVN0Aa5WXup3Zcct5UqH8LJks6G6tE5P55tI9t2XDU1rRwk0FOazBpJBeEkT9fr0t6Fv5l7oQS5pfF2ZNLuVYHUk-mn\" target=\"_blank\">Sofia Tilbury</a>, who counts Candice Swanepoel, Shanina Shaik, Sienna Miller, and Irina Shayk as clients. She also happens to be the niece of Charlotte Tilbury, one of the most famous makeup artists of all time, so she has a few tricks up her sleeve worth noting. She revealed her top four makeup tips to look younger, and they're all surprisingly easy to do. From the first step she does on every face she works on to the lip-enhancing technique that creates a full pout, below are her best tips for a youthful glow. </p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/284330/makeup-tips-to-look-younger-284330-1581527876245-main.1200x1600uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p>\"Hydration is essential!\" Sofia says. \"I never do makeup without <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/ext?tl=C62GIamcokapZXmynp4iHnoPXi2rkHMSgNL52Gmjlx2wXuJl2vvNcPgaPtWSJ46R_SKDZYiELGDY4kV8fbmpu4gJPf-4UOPaxHLGc0MESCWfEBJ84O-SNOPTEQiHERCvDLb1SeP-tKOfW-bQr3X3DtBrEeAxMbIXZJimJuuq6UArKz0bNOsclplf8zGsk18SLvTGhr3NI7qwCJvHYGwbnRabw_9dJVN8fFrLFkH8fHMrIgnI8RJPkwWgx5CvqGAzWSuKR_EBAnltHUJQlNti5Yru1rSVbQjv-HgNjceE4T-5Z5NGemoeAeNfAvbJh6dekz0MV1iuDDFmTzyF4pnzVMj33bFxj0C05K-nPBhEKpXRQi4ufT_wbsPHN5RCfY3YakUGSg6y1VNvO0LR_XURqzyDHgDS3w\" target=\"_blank\">Magic Cream</a>. Whenever I'm working with a celebrity client, I massage this all over the skin to create a dewy, glowing base while reducing the look of fine lines and wrinkles.\" Starting off with an ultra-hydrating moisturizer will get the blood flowing throughout your face and plump up any pesky lines you may have. </p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/284330/makeup-tips-to-look-younger-284330-1581534254722-main.1080x1350uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/284330/makeup-tips-to-look-younger-284330-1581572732307-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/284330/makeup-tips-to-look-younger-284330-1581572878946-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/284330/makeup-tips-to-look-younger-284330-1581573014697-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/284330/makeup-tips-to-look-younger-284330-1581573075810-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p>\"Heavy, cakey powder is the enemy of mature skin! I recommend using a super-finely milled powder like <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/ext?tl=T8HKu9SsoOvY5ZqMBVzmJIcdZSdWvSWyW0qZFK5zkJI8giZlx0ZpbfqsuWyrOPzxvNRfKvucUH1B-5VReM4zn5s-g99rRX3KlwaMoa7FqDPuJ0vrOvBR-1kuvzV6j0M5Ifw9n-WirhaulqYUvd56E10-lLFOfHgvt6CU-g27F5WPl1itsJxQKh8-eY4iai4HZ3IFmfRWeBxVinI\" target=\"_blank\">Airbrush Flawless Finish</a> on your T-zone, leaving the high points of your face glowing and free from powder,\" explains Sofia. </p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/284330/makeup-tips-to-look-younger-284330-1581534330787-main.1080x1274uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/284330/makeup-tips-to-look-younger-284330-1581573323064-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/284330/makeup-tips-to-look-younger-284330-1587145219483-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/284330/makeup-tips-to-look-younger-284330-1581573971459-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/284330/makeup-tips-to-look-younger-284330-1581574034924-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p>\"People are so afraid of shimmering formulas—especially on mature skin—but it is actually an amazing way to attract light to the face, blurring the look of fine lines and wrinkles,\" Sofia reveals. \"When creating a really glowy, youthful look, I like to use Charlotte’s cream eye shadow, <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/ext?tl=a3nQY2sv55epuD4_Znl98LEmpEY5R1BXzSJIMEoy1SA7XCwhqM_iJSQdj0nu57ZiHjrfZxWaQzdbceoHDaR4Rb9jNz8jNJor6-B4DrbTdvCqxnpB7nkimeb94_V6OkEHQb381lNtGLsoUQWvN3SVkHHrRXUWI2gxb-uICRoyyflk2XOY8h0YbZ1cvq6ndcTt\" target=\"_blank\">Eyes to Mesmerise</a> in Jean, on the eyes for maximum impact with minimum effort. It is so easy to use. You can even apply it with your fingers, washing the color all over the lids, into the inner corners, and along the lower lash line to give the appearance of brighter, wider-looking eyes. Then, simply curl your lashes and add plenty of volumizing mascara!\" So with just one creamy, champagne-colored eye shadow, you can create the look of brighter, wider eyes using this technique. </p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/284330/makeup-tips-to-look-younger-284330-1581534473539-main.1080x1277uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/284330/makeup-tips-to-look-younger-284330-1581574197929-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/284330/makeup-tips-to-look-younger-284330-1581574298754-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/284330/makeup-tips-to-look-younger-284330-1581576800777-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/284330/makeup-tips-to-look-younger-284330-1581577190962-main.800x1067uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p>\"As we age, our lips tend to lose their fullness and can even start to fade in color, so lip liner is essential! Take the <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/ext?tl=xPnSMeHhdCRxRfj89hEIaitkZap4OtYH9B0PwNWrq-AgLJqU9wpY3a4XPBfhuu4lSGFjDjqJJs-vuPS6khTHdukRvz_XawYORtAD-Up328XR7XRF7OM_Lwo9KQxUl9nGNl8lE9GhrZ_2W-woAFGw3FTfyvQm7xNB1xPfvsRIyFMbnq4qLlTFJWG_VvvafQ\" target=\"_blank\">Lip Cheat in Pillow Talk</a> and trace the line of the lips, really focusing on creating a defined Cupid's bow. I'm a real lip-liner girl, so I do this every day. You can instantly cheat and redefine the look of your lips for a youthful, perfected pout.\"</p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/284330/makeup-tips-to-look-younger-284330-1581534432463-main.1080x1172uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img Best","link":"http://feeds.whowhatwear.com/~r/WhoWhatWear/~3/dBe4blaG5aQ/best-solid-perfumes","description":"<p><a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/best-places-to-buy-perfume-online\" target=\"_blank\">Perfume</a> rollerballs and travel-size sprays get all the love and attention where on-the-go fragrance is concerned, but we're here to say solid perfumes are the best, most underrated way to keep your <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/most-popular-designer-perfumes\" target=\"_blank\">signature scent</a> beautifully <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/long-lasting-perfumes\" target=\"_blank\">intact all day long</a>.</p><p>Not only are solid perfumes pint-size and effortlessly compatible with even <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/backup-tote-bag\" target=\"_blank\">the teeniest of tiny handbags</a>, but they're also spill-proof and laced with truly skin-loving ingredients (think lush oils like coconut, sweet almond, jojoba, and more) that kill two birds with one stone by <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/best-organic-moisturizers/slide3\" target=\"_blank\">moisturizing your skin</a> and dosing you with fragrance. Oh, and did we mention the super-chic packaging? We love that so many of our favorite solid perfumes are meticulously packaged in the prettiest, most display-worthy compacts—from seashells to charms to gold-encrusted adornments. Below, we're sharing nine of the best-smelling solid perfumes along with the formulas they pair magically with. Keep scrolling!</p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288927/best-solid-perfumes-288927-1599077901183-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption>Key fragrance notes: grapefruit, quince, white musk, and jasmine. The name says it all! This elegant and demure solid perfume from Chanel allows you to touch up on the go—anytime, anywhere!</figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288927/best-solid-perfumes-288927-1599077905330-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288927/best-solid-perfumes-288927-1599077909484-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption>Key fragrance notes: amber/patchouli accord, rose, cinnamon, and black-currant buds. We highly recommend this solid version of one of our all-time favorite fragrances from Diptyque that is juicy, warm, and a little bit spicy. For long-lasting wear, the brand recommends you apply on your main pulse points (like the wrists, the insides of your elbows, the base of your neck, behind your ears, and atop your décolleté).</figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288927/best-solid-perfumes-288927-1599077914039-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288927/best-solid-perfumes-288927-1599077918068-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption>Key fragrance notes: lime, iris, rose, ginger, patchouli, civet, and musk. The ingredients this solid perfume from Le Labo is made out of are almost as decadent as the classic, velvety scent. With sensitive skin in mind, it's alcohol-free and utilizes a hydrating blend of coconut, sweet almond, and soybean oils.</figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288927/best-solid-perfumes-288927-1599077924315-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288927/best-solid-perfumes-288927-1599077927916-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption>Key fragrance notes: mandarin, basil, and amberwood. Lime Basil & Mandarin is one of Jo Malone's most signature scents, and they have a lot! We love the idea of throwing this in our tiniest purse, gym bag, or duffel and bringing it anywhere our post-quarantine travels take us. </figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288927/best-solid-perfumes-288927-1599077932124-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288927/best-solid-perfumes-288927-1599077936191-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption>Key fragrance notes: jasmine trinity, bergamot, saffron, rose, and dark patchouli. Trust us. It doesn't get any more decadent than this rich, stunning scent that beautifully amplifies once you've applied it to your pulse points. It boasts three different types of delicate jasmine flowers, and, thanks to ingredients like jojoba oil and beeswax, dry skin will lap it up. (You can even apply it to the parched ends of your hair!)</figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288927/best-solid-perfumes-288927-1599077941257-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288927/best-solid-perfumes-288927-1599077946285-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption>Key fragrance notes: geranium, vetiver, ylang-ylang, lavender, and patchouli. As if the stunning seashell compact wasn't enough to get you to pull out your credit card, this organic, botanical-based fragrance will seal the deal. The brand makes multiple scents, but this is our favorite floral profile. In fact, the ingredients are so healing you can dab it on as an impromptu scar treatment.</figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288927/best-solid-perfumes-288927-1599077950638-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288927/best-solid-perfumes-288927-1599077955034-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption>Key fragrance notes: gardenia, tea leaves, sweet orange, and jasmine. Not only do we love this solid perfume thanks to its clean, nontoxic ingredients, but we also love it because it is easy on the wallet, is handbag ready, and is the next best thing to a tropical vacay in Tahiti. (It's amazing across the chest and over the collarbones!) </figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288927/best-solid-perfumes-288927-1599077957906-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288927/best-solid-perfumes-288927-1599077961937-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption>Key fragrance notes: rose, lily, tuberose, and orange flower. Solid perfumes reign supreme when it comes to stunning packaging. We're beyond smitten with how vanity friendly this limited-edition perfume compact is from fragrance and beauty legend Estée Lauder. And the scent is just as covetable. (Think a rich bouquet starring all of your favorite flowers.)</figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288927/best-solid-perfumes-288927-1599077967357-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288927/best-solid-perfumes-288927-1599077971851-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption>Key fragrance notes: strawberry, vanilla, lavender, sage. Quit","link":"http://feeds.whowhatwear.com/~r/WhoWhatWear/~3/5rGM0mel1Ig/best-swimsuit-trends","description":"<p><strong>Shop Like an Editor</strong> <em>is a Who What Wear column where our senior editor <a class=\"link link--story\" href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/ext?tl=QWdZtpXdXsGcB50TP30EGvYuWrrDUGntIMRzYtxEByuJ-zJnC21JBivgQLj4OFq329-BlbzLPtJE1Ly65hY\"><span class=\"s2\">Kristen Nichols</span></a> shares her latest fashion finds.</em></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599176209781-main.0x800uc.gif\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p class=\"p1\">Though summer may be winding down, I’m leaning heavily into <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/popular-swimsuits\" target=\"_blank\">swimwear</a> right now. Inspired by some of the best <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/swimwear-trends-2020\" target=\"_blank\">swimsuit trends</a> of the season, I’ve been trying out my favorite styles. While I’ve been wearing swimsuits for a backyard dip in the pool, I’ve also been experimenting by mixing swimwear into my everyday outfits—whether it’s a bikini top paired with high-waisted trousers or a sparkly bikini underneath a breezy linen dress.</p><p class=\"p1\">My style is part minimalist, part maximalist—and you’ll see evidence of both here. I often gravitate to the clean, classic lines of a solid <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/splash/zorxT7yBj?w=3705090\"><span class=\"s1\">one-shoulder swimsuit</span></a>, but you’ll also spot me wearing more high-drama items like a golden <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/ext?tl=okLAW-sWZLXCMk7BQsffAqVm_n9CwqUfUxl96oblKkyBnTwr2sSiQ1cp17Cl0Qov95SYYj86-jycMve985Sb6tMeKZsQyMsf8pEAC23FYQ1tcLH4Vp_0cqWobzlkQWp2o66AuM1XSx3SM7BvLQ\"><span class=\"s1\">ruched one-piece</span></a> from <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/isa-boulder-brand-review\"><span class=\"s1\">Isa Boulder</span></a> or an ‘80s-inspired ruffled swimsuit. Even when I keep things simple, though, I like to layer in jewelry like statement earrings or a chain necklace to add some dimension to the look. Ahead, see how I'm wearing the 7 swimsuit trends I can’t quit and shop my top edit.</p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599179874204-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption>I first spotted Indonesian brand Isa Boulder on Instagram earlier this year and instantly fell for their unique ruched swimsuits. Finished with underwire cups and a satin-like material, their designs are part of the larger lingerie-inspired swimwear trend we're seeing right now. While this is stunning to wear on its own, it also works as a great transitional piece to wear with trousers as we head into fall since lingerie pieces will be huge for the season ahead.</figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599182155467-main.1301x1805uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599185649550-main.1400x1779uc.jpg\"><figcaption>Shop the matching Second Wave Bikini Bottoms ($40).</figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599190432177-main.2000x3000uc.jpg\"><figcaption>Shop the matching Emma Bikini Briefs ($160).</figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1598943030402-main.1080x1350uc.jpg\"><figcaption>With the bra top trend in full swing, I've been adopting bikinis as tops for a look to wear beyond the pool or beach. Square necklines are the silhouette I've been gravitating to because of their clean lines that easily pass for a crop top. Here, I styled a top from Monday Swimwear with a pair of belted high-waist trousers and strappy sandals. Next month, I'd wear the same look but add a loose blazer and sleek ankle boots.</figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1598943186682-main.1366x2048uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599187393409-main.1280x1920uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599189765760-main.1128x2000uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599179208097-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption>One-shoulder swimsuits are the minimalist trend that has been everywhere this summer but I think the silhouette is only picking up steam. Moving into fall, we'll be seeing one-shoulder tops take off, so this is the perfect piece to wear later in place of a bodysuit. I particularly love this version from Jade Swim—it has a beautiful open back and a strap that wraps around from the side to the shoulder which you can see in the product shot below.</figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599166246562-main.1391x1854uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599166194737-main.1001x1400uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599188411558-main.1128x2000uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599210325733-main.1127x1500uc.jpg\"><figcaption>High-shine lurex swimsuits have been around for a bit now, but seem to get more and more popular each season. Italian brand Oséree definitely put them on the map with their signature sparkly fabrics that glisten as they catch the sun. I love the subtle shine of this black bikini that adds just the right touch of glamour to an otherwise classic style.</figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599162677710-main.1062x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599166061160-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599170875882-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599162358144-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption>One of the most unique swimsuit shapes on my radar? Sleeved versions. I've really fallen hard for this fresh take on swimwear that stands out from the rest. Here, I'm wearing a set from Same Swim that has a rash guard top and high-rise bottoms. I especially love this one-piece from Devon Windsor that has a plunging neckline and cool, textured fabric. This is yet another piece that I can imagine wearing in place of a top with trousers or jeans.</figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599191165310-main.1262x1799uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599165870302-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599170115140-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599194553184-main.1080x1350uc.jpg\"><figcaption>While I tend to stick with solids over prints, I couldn't resist the cool zebra pattens that have been everywhere recently. _1870838db5471667.webp","https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599191165310-main.1262x1799uc.jpg":"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/myreaderx10/cdn15@2020_3/2020/09/05/08-42-29-376_fa2eee8709d2e2a5.webp","https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599165870302-main.800x0uc.jpg":"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/myreaderx1/cdn57@2020_4/2020/09/05/08-42-11-419_6009095ac99755e2.webp","https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599170115140-main.800x0uc.jpg":"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/myreaderx32/cdn99@2020_3/2020/09/05/08-43-25-516_93a1a578a921a7dc.webp","https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599194553184-main.1080x1350uc.jpg":"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/myreaderx32/cdn5@2020_5/2020/09/05/08-42-32-797_06c2bf6691f87a88.webp","https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599194733516-main.800x0uc.jpg":"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/myreaderx31/cdn47@2020_4/2020/09/05/08-41-36-527_7c95ccdfca7f3013.webp","https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599194798082-main.800x0uc.jpg":"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/myreaderx30/cdn45@2020_2/2020/09/05/08-42-55-552_52adbec48f48c001.webp","https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288916/best-swimsuit-trends-288916-1599194606278-main.2000x3000uc.jpg":"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/myreaderx15/cdn1@2020_3/2020/09/05/08-42-56-172_c278d16b3d3a6187.webp","http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/WhoWhatWear/~4/5rGM0mel1Ig":"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/myreaderx5oss/cdn92@2020_3/2020/09/05/08-42-36-131_55eb78f405efee16.webp"},"publishedOrCreatedDate":1599295287274},{"createdTime":"2020-09-05 16:41:27","updatedTime":"2020-09-05 16:41:27","title":"How to Remove Scuff Marks From Shoes","link":"http://feeds.whowhatwear.com/~r/WhoWhatWear/~3/QzoZw_Hw4LI/how-to-remove-scuff-marks-from-shoes","description":"<p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/249660/how-to-remove-scuff-marks-from-shoes-249660-1599085259038-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p>There’s an elusively misattributed quote (Marilyn Monroe? Bette Midler? We may never know) we love returning to: “Give a girl the right shoes, and she can conquer the world.” While we’re partial to believing that someone can conquer the world regardless of footwear, having the perfect pair of shoes certainly can’t hurt.</p><p>One of the keys to the <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/how-to-clean-suede-boots\" target=\"_blank\">perfect pair of shoes</a> is keeping them clean, clear, and scuff-free. Whether you’re looking to shine up your favorite pair of <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/how-to-clean-patent-leather\" target=\"_blank\">patent leather</a> pumps or <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/flats-with-arch-support\" target=\"_blank\">everyday flats</a>, here are five of our favorite methods on how to remove scuff marks from shoes, using a handful of items you likely already have on hand.</p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/249660/how-to-remove-scuff-marks-from-shoes-249660-1599085286608-main.1200x1365uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><span>Unless your shoes contain a <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/how-to-clean-white-vans\" target=\"_blank\">fabric</a> that’s likely to be on the dry clean–only list—satin, for example—a small amount of </span><span>gentle laundry detergent</span><span> can offer the perfect fix. Mix a few drops of detergent in a small amount of lukewarm water, then use a clean cloth to dab the scuff marks. Once they’ve been removed, wipe away any residue with a second clean cloth.</span></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/249660/how-to-remove-scuff-marks-from-shoes-249660-1519345055553-main.1200x1365uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/249660/how-to-remove-scuff-marks-from-shoes-249660-1599085302828-main.1200x1365uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><span>While most mistakes can’t simply be erased, scuff marks on shoes are thankfully an exception. After testing a less conspicuous area of a shoe, use circular motions to gently buff the scuff marks with an eraser. This method works especially well for vinyl and <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/how-to-clean-white-leather-shoes\" target=\"_blank\">patent leather shoes</a>. We recommend using a </span><span>white eraser</span><span> in order to avoid the gummy pink residue you remember from grade school.</span></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/249660/how-to-remove-scuff-marks-from-shoes-249660-1519345145785-main.1200x1365uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/249660/how-to-remove-scuff-marks-from-shoes-249660-1599085312107-main.1200x1365uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><span>In addition to removing nail polish, this medicine cabinet staple can also work wonders in helping to remove scuff marks from shoes. Apply a small amount of nail polish remover to a cotton ball, then polish the scuff marks using focused, circular motions. Again, testing on a less noticeable section of the shoe beforehand is always wise, but this method tends to work well for a variety of fabrics and types of shoes, from patent leather heels to <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/how-to-clean-white-sneakers\" target=\"_blank\">basic sneakers</a>.</span></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/249660/how-to-remove-scuff-marks-from-shoes-249660-1519345456901-main.1200x1365uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/249660/how-to-remove-scuff-marks-from-shoes-249660-1599085320723-main.1200x1365uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><span>It’s no secret that baking soda has a wide range of cleaning applications, and you can add removing scuff marks from shoes to the list. Combine a small amount of baking soda (1 to 2 tablespoons should do the trick) with warm water. Mix the paste to an even consistency, then apply directly to the scuff marks. Use a cloth to polish the shoes, then remove the residue with a second clean cloth.</span></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/249660/how-to-remove-scuff-marks-from-shoes-249660-1519345615025-main.1200x1365uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/249660/how-to-remove-scuff-marks-from-shoes-249660-1599085337490-main.1200x1365uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><strong><span>Harnessing the same technology as baking soda, toothpaste can be used to achieve similar results. Apply a small amount of toothpaste to a clean cloth, then use this to polish the scuff marks. Avoid using a chemical-heavy, whitening, or gel toothpaste. Use a second, damp cloth to wipe away the marks and toothpaste, and allow the shoes to air-dry.</span></strong></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/249660/how-to-remove-scuff-marks-from-shoes-249660-1599085589824-main.1200x1200uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><em>Once those scuffs are out, learn <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/how-to-clean-white-sneakers\" target=\"_blank\">nine easy hacks to keep white sneakers clean</a>.</em></p><p><em>This post was originally published at an earlier date and has since been updated.</em></p><img src=\"http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/WhoWhatWear/~4/QzoZw_Hw4LI\" height=\"1\" width=\"1\" <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/ext?tl=sqtU39tbOvol6R4iXjSco3rrtEeRkQ9JyWt5R-Ue8Zk6n5zVv4MKyRqg9XCQ3162\" target=\"_blank\">The Grateful Gardenia</a>. Originally from Texas, the 58-year-old style guru is now settled in Los Angeles with her husband, son, and dog, Buster. She’s worked as a Dallas Cowboys cheerleader, flight attendant, actor, jewelry designer, and beyond. In other words, she has a ton of experience and an equally cool personal style. Melissa Meyers is a Los Angeles–based influencer with a focus on beauty, style, travel, and wellness. Her blog, <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/ext?tl=H_G7jbeYVy2gl5RHijRvPhgDiRgQmn6iFTLuet0DxPI3ib_-d7FGJD20cYw\" target=\"_blank\">The Glow Girl</a>, aims to empower women to embrace the best version of themselves, age gracefully, and cultivate a glow from the inside out. Oh, and don’t forget to follow them at <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/ext?tl=n1_2-E4AXc3u1I9ZcXtRjLDrBSy8bpHXbzz44qDNccIY9pXKl11QFpZs5nMwrSXHmAa7f0nKw0oxXQDYP80LrRqnMP53aIT1bq4\" target=\"_blank\">@janetgunngratefulgardenia</a> and <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/ext?tl=IvgHDPfRlJleSesF1oS09j4nDchFgqLFPziEhpqaAeiwAWNg3TqbQgX6EIIAh91c92WmiMonM1Ctli34E9c\" target=\"_blank\">@melissameyers</a>.</em></p><p>We routinely turn to <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/accessories-for-women-over-50\" target=\"_blank\">over-50 influencers</a> Janet Gunn and Melissa Meyers for sartorial guidance. Of course, age has absolutely nothing to do with what you should or shouldn’t wear, but their specific advice is often intriguing given their expertise over the years fine-tuning their wardrobes. On that note, we thought we’d focus next on some of the specific <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/best-comfortable-jeans\" target=\"_blank\">denim silhouettes</a> this duo wears on repeat. More specifically, we thought there could be interest in learning about the jeans they love to wear, along with outfits to match for some inspiration.</p><p>With all that in mind, keep scrolling to see the jeans outfits Gunn and Meyers wear often because they're easy and versatile in nature. You’ll also uncover some shopping inspo as well if you’re looking to add a fresh piece or two into your wardrobe.</p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288765/denim-outfits-over-50-288765-1598284622395-image.1200x1800uc.jpg\"><figcaption>We love high-waisted jeans for their shape and style. 16:41:27","updatedTime":"2020-09-05 16:41:27","title":"9 Color Trends We're About to See Everywhere This Fall","link":"http://feeds.whowhatwear.com/~r/WhoWhatWear/~3/rsMdecXXlLU/fall-color-trends-2020","description":"<p class=\"p1\">While we're just settling into <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/cheap-summer-pieces-from-amazon\" target=\"_blank\">summer</a> right now, there’s no question we fashion folks are already looking ahead to some of the <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/milan-fashion-week-fall-winter-2020\" target=\"_blank\">biggest trends</a> set to dominate come September. Today we’re focusing on <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/spring-summer-color-trends-2020\" target=\"_blank\">color trends</a> (my personal favorite subject) and looking to the <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/new-york-fashion-week-fall-winter-2020/\" target=\"_blank\">F/W 20 runways</a> to determine which hues will reign supreme for the rest of the year.</p><p class=\"p2\"><span class=\"s1\">“The color palette for fall/winter 2020 highlights our desire for versatile, timeless color—reflecting a less-is-more mindset,” explains Leatrice Eiseman, executive director of the Pantone Color Institute, “colors whose timelessness and versatility convey a level of functionality and at the same time lend themselves to unique color statements that stand out.”</span></p><p class=\"p1\">From rich and deep burgundy hues to asphalt gray and unexpected pops of orange, below we’re sharing the biggest color trends we’re about to see everywhere. Get ahead of the curve by shopping the hues right now.</p><p>We're no strangers to seeing burgundy in fall, and this year, we saw the gamut of shades, from sultry, cherry reds to deep and dark wine hues. Robust reds were seen on head-to-toe looks in a plethora of textures and fabrics from leather capes to relaxed knits, adding a sophisticated touch to fall ensembles.</p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1585278723945-main.2732x4098uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1594095533656-main.1050x1370uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p>While practically every shade of blue had its moment on the fall runways (we particularly love refreshing powder blue and navy), it was the vibrant and bold strong blue hues that really caught our eye—most notably seen on a plethora of beautiful coats and dresses. </p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1585286186304-main.2667x4000uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1585286901645-main.1546x2453uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1599001343359-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1585332727462-main.2100x2940uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p>Gray is having a major moment for F/W 20. The neutral hue dominated the runways in head-to-toe looks. The shade came in various fabrics, lengths, and silhouettes, from suits to chunky knits and striking overcoats. The key to the tonal look is mixing various shades (and fabrics) within your ensemble, from darker ash tones to lighter heather shades.</p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1585280827986-main.2837x4256uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1585280617898-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1585281720689-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1585282239292-main.1604x2555uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1599001584503-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1599001683786-main.2100x2940uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p>The green-yellow shade was a fresh addition to the F/W runways, seen on tweed skirt suits, silk dresses, and knits. The color feels botanical and crisp and will unquestionably add an optimistic touch to your fall neutrals.</p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1585288350632-main.2708x4283uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1585287805461-main.2003x4043uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1585288008953-main.2837x4256uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1585287347080-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1599002061631-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1599002394603-main.1500x1500uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p>Designers from Isabel Marant to Dior brought us dreamy (and creamy!) head-to-toe ensembles in warm off-white shades. Opt for ivory suiting or almond milk–hued knits for an elegant, modern, and luxurious look.</p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1585282785816-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1585283150050-main.3280x4920uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1585282905887-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1585283222890-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1594096844261-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1594096975861-main.1333x2000uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p>Time to enjoy some winter citrus! Radiant and lively orange hues were seen paired with everything from blue denim to brown leather, exuding a sense of confidence, creativity, and happiness.</p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1585289760815-main.1366x2049uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1585289887217-main.3456x5184uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1585328299739-main.2837x4256uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1594097935249-main.1128x2000uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1599002610393-main.1440x1800uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p>The F/W runways declared that black is anything but boring in 2020. The color was seen in all silhouettes and styles, from cutouts to fringe, puff sleeves to capes—breathing new life into the hue.</p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1585284313235-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1585285074712-main.2374x3955uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1585284578794-main.3264x5000uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1585285453672-main.2732x4098uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1599002708248-main.800x0uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1594098144210-main.2340x2925uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p>Beige has unquestionably been the fashion world's favorite hue this past year, and the trend shows no signs of slowing down. Beige tones came in various shades on the runways, from pale-pink camel to warm and sandy tones, but we're really loving the deeper woodsy tan and toffee coloring seen on luxe fabrics such as leather.</p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/286406/fall-color-trends-2020-286406-1585327435481-main.2837x4256uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288969/meghan-markle-prince-harry-netflix-288969-1599092100188-main.1200x900uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p>Hollywood, say hello to Harry and Meghan, your friendly new neighborhood producers. The formerly royal couple have been hard at work <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/meghan-markle-princess-diana-commemoration\" target=\"_blank\">helping out with Los Angeles charities</a> since moving to California, but now they're expanding their repertoire. According to <em><a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/ext?tl=PhLtaCuhGPIj8RWMqFEtZzR_O1Ub0_NxU2QxH1ujcgHFEitc9zAz6ru5Jr3WgjaRhkZbdBjLxasw8AYIoSh4Nc810NqjZbNDHueNQ_JRfr7d-ViL_bwz-KE5Qg\" target=\"_blank\">The New York Times</a></em>, Prince Harry and Meghan Markle have just signed a \"megawatt\" Netflix contract. </p><p>They have officially started a new production company, just like another high-profile couple did when embarking on a new chapter: Barack and <a href=\"https://www.whowhatwear.com/michelle-obama-basics\" target=\"_blank\">Michelle Obama</a>. The <em>NYT </em>explains that Harry and Meghan signed \"a multiyear deal with Netflix, which will pay them to make documentaries, docu-series, feature films, scripted shows, and children’s programming.\" Intrigued? Me too. A representative told the newspaper that Meghan is not planning to resume her acting career, but she and Harry may be featured in documentary films. In other words, expect them to take a more behind-the-scenes role overall. Stay tuned as we learn more about the exciting news. </p><p><figure><img Take it from experience—it's easy to fall into a black hole of shopping when the site stocks everything from dresses to swimsuits at an attractive price-point, which is why I tapped one of ASOS' insiders, Lotte Williams, to clue me in to some of the best shopping picks from the retailer now.</p><p><figure><img src=\"https://cdn.cliqueinc.com/posts/288974/asos-shopping-insider-288974-1599232282989-main.1200x900uc.jpg\"><figcaption></figcaption></figure></p><p>Williams has a knack for uncovering the coolest picks from the site and her outfits always find their way into my saved folder. things from ASOS,\" she said, \"which, TBH, even if I wasn’t an insider I’d be doing anyway!\"</p><p>With that, Williams is sharing the contents of her virtual shopping cart with us and her finds are
